\noindent

An early study in the field of firearm examination was executed by \citet{hamby} and consists of over 300 sets of bullets sent out to firearm examiners worldwide.
Each of these sets consists of 20 bullets with known provenance and 15 questioned bullets: two bullets each were fired from ten consecutively manufactured barrels of P-85 Ruger firearms. Barrels are labeled 1 - 10, and the bullets are labelled as bullet 1 and bullet 2 from a particular barrel. %These two bullets were labeled as bullets 1 and 2 from barrels 1 through 10.
The remaining fifteen bullets were each fired from one of the ten barrels (such that at at least one and at most 4 bullets came from the same barrel) and labeled with uppercase letters. Firearms examiners are then asked to match the questioned bullets to the corresponding barrels.

Each barrel has six land engraved areas resulting from firing the gun; together with the Barrel and Bullet identifiers, the land identifier can be used to identify a single digital scan stored in x3p format\citep{x3p}.

These scans have an additional advantage over conventional sets of physical bullets: it is much easier to share the digital data.
The NIST database \citep{nist} contains the raw data for this study as well as many others.
Information about the individual scans is provided in \autoref{meta}; here, each row describes a scan of a single bullet land, its location on disk after the download, whether the corresponding land shows damage unrelated to the firing, and its relationship to Hamby set 173 bullet 1 from the same barrel.

\autoref{features} consists of a description of all features describing pairwise comparisons of scans. These features are aimed to distinguish between pairs of scans from the same source (corresponding to two bullets fired from the same barrel) and two different sources (corresponding to bullets fired from different barrels).
\autoref{fig:densities} gives an overview of some of the features in the `hamby-comparisons.csv` file. Values from same-source comparisons are shown in orange, different-source comparisons are shown in grey. Area under the curve (AUC) is a value between 0 and 1 describing the strength of one feature's strength in discriminating between same-source and different-source comparisons. The closer values are to 1, the better they discriminate.


