Finally, csafe-rf2.rds is the binary file containing the random forest object fitted on the features in \texttt{hamby-comparisons.csv}. Random forests \citep{breiman} are a machine-learning method using an ensemble of decision trees.
This random forest model is used to assess the similarity of two scans, with an output prediction of 0 indicative of dissimilarity between the scans, and an output prediction near 1 indicative of similarity between the scans. In addition to containing the weights used to make predictions, the fitted model also contains a record of the predictions made during the fitting process; and the features used to fit the model to the original set of scans. It is important to archive not only the code used to fit this model, but also the intermediate data, derived features, and full fitted model object, so that when the model is re-fit we have a record of changes between versions of the random forest models.


The random forest object `csafe\_rf2` has an overall out-of-bag error rate estimated as 0.32\%. Out of the total 81,003 pairwise comparisons of the `hamby-comparisons.csv` data 80,743 comparisons or 99.68\% are correctly classified as same-source or different-source pairs.

